Bubble sorting is a simple sorting algorithm that works by repeatedly stepping through the list to be sorted, comparing each adjacent pair and swapping them if they are in the wrong order. The algorithm gets its name from the way larger elements "bubble" to the top of the list as sorting progresses.

Here is the algorithm pseudocode for bubble sorting:

```
function BubbleSort(arr) {
    for (int i = 0; i < arr.length - 1; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < arr.length - i - 1; j++) {
            if (arr[j] > arr[j + 1]) {
                swap(arr, j, j + 1);
            }
        }
    }
    return arr;
}

// Function to swap elements at indices i and j
function swap(arr, i, j) {
    let temp = arr[i];
    arr[i] = arr[j];
    arr[j] = temp;
}
```

This algorithm works by comparing the `j`-th and `j + 1`-th elements of the array and swapping them if the `j`-th element is greater than the `j + 1`-th element. This process is repeated for each pair of adjacent elements until there is only one element left in the array, which is now sorted.

The `for` loop in the algorithm steps through the array from index `0` to `arr.length - 1`, which is the length of the array minus 1 because the last element is already sorted. The `for` loop inside the `for` loop steps through each pair of adjacent elements, comparing them and swapping them if necessary.

The `swap` function is a helper function that takes the array and the indices of the elements to be swapped as parameters and performs the swap operation.
